	<tr>
		<td colspan="2"><hr class="sep" /><div class="quotetitle">Sandfish wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">@tepples - Do you know who was talking about the Rom hack?</div><br />Nobody in particular, but it would probably be the best way to incorporate mouse support into an existing NES game. The Fairlight release of Mario Paint went the other way: the trainer made it compatible with the standard controller.<br /><br /><div class="quotetitle"><b>Quote:</b></div><div class="quotecontent">If someone puts our plans into pratice I'd help as good as I can <br />(That's just wirering and soldering so far so I just can rebuild)</div>
<br />As far as I can tell, the adapter would just involve cutting off one end of a Super NES extension cord and one end of an NES extension cord and soldering the corresponding wires together, or cutting up an NES controller and Super NES mouse and putting some sort of standard connector in the middle (like the inline release on an original Xbox controller) so that one can swap their plugs. I suggested the clock filter circuit only to make it possible to hack games that use the DPCM channel for drums or display timing.

		

		</td>
	</tr>
	</table>


